  "prompt": "How can I simplify [math]\\frac{1}{1+x^{m-n}}+ \\frac{1}{1+x^{n-m}}?[/math]",
  "response": "To simplify the expression \\(\\frac{1}{1+x^{m-n}}+ \\frac{1}{1+x^{n-m}}\\), we can observe that \\(m\\) and \\(n\\) are integers, and the term \\(x^{m-n}\\) and \\(x^{n-m}\\) are reciprocals of each other. Here's how we can proceed with the simplification:\n\nLet's denote \\(a = x^{m-n}\\). Thus the expression becomes:\n\n\\[\n\\frac{1}{1+a} + \\frac{1}{1+\\frac{1}{a}}\n\\]\n\nNext, simplify the second term:\n\n\\[\n\\frac{1}{1+\\frac{1}{a}} = \\frac{1}{\\frac{a+1}{a}} = \\frac{a}{a+1}\n\\]\n\nNow our expression is:\n\n\\[\n\\frac{1}{1+a} + \\frac{a}{a+1}\n\\]\n\nSince \\(\\frac{a}{a+1} = 1 - \\frac{1}{a+1}\\), we get:\n\n\\[\n\\frac{1}{1+a} + 1 - \\frac{1}{1+a}\n\\]\n\nNotice that:\n\n\\[\n\\frac{1}{1+a} - \\frac{1}{1+a} = 0\n\\]\n\nSo the expression simplifies to:\n\n\\[\n1 - 0 = 1\n\\]\n\nTherefore, the simplified form of \\(\\frac{1}{1+x^{m-n}} + \\frac{1}{1+x^{n-m}}\\) is:\n\n\\[\n1\n\\]",
